# --- Shopify Storefront API (headless) ---
# Copy to `.env.local` and fill in from your Shopify Headless sales channel.
# These are read client-side, so they MUST be VITE_-prefixed. The Storefront
# access token is a PUBLIC token — safe to ship in the browser bundle.
#
# Leave these unset to develop against the local dev fixtures. As soon as both
# DOMAIN and TOKEN are present, the app fetches live catalog + cart from Shopify.

VITE_SHOPIFY_STORE_DOMAIN=your-store.myshopify.com
VITE_SHOPIFY_STOREFRONT_TOKEN=your-storefront-access-token

# Optional — Storefront API version. Defaults to 2025-01 if unset.
# VITE_SHOPIFY_API_VERSION=2025-01


# --- Customer accounts (login / auth) ---
# Real auth uses Shopify's Customer Account API (OAuth 2.0 + PKCE, passwordless).
# Classic Storefront password auth was removed in API 2025-04, so this is the
# only supported path. To keep tokens off the browser (safest), the OAuth flow
# runs through a small serverless BFF in `/api` — the client secret and tokens
# never reach the bundle. See docs/shopify.md and the plan for the full flow.

# Client-side flag: set to "true" ONLY where the /api functions are running
# (prod, or `vercel dev`). Left unset, the app uses the dev fixture auth so the
# account UI stays navigable under plain `vite` with no Shopify and no backend.
# VITE_CUSTOMER_AUTH_ENABLED=true

# Server-only — these are SECRETS. They are read by the /api functions and MUST
# NOT be VITE_-prefixed (that would ship them in the browser bundle). Set them in
# your host's env (Vercel/Netlify/Cloudflare) and in .env.local for `vercel dev`.
#
#   SHOPIFY_SHOP_DOMAIN=your-store.myshopify.com
#   SHOPIFY_SHOP_ID=72829075558                         # numeric id in the endpoint URLs
#   SHOPIFY_CUSTOMER_CLIENT_ID=xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx
#   SHOPIFY_CUSTOMER_CLIENT_SECRET=...                  # confidential client secret
#   SHOPIFY_STOREFRONT_TOKEN=your-storefront-access-token  # reused for cart linking
#   APP_ORIGIN=https://your-app.vercel.app              # site origin the BFF redirects back to
#   COOKIE_SECRET=<64+ random hex chars>                # signs the transient OAuth cookie
#   # SHOPIFY_CUSTOMER_API_VERSION=2026-07              # optional; defaults in code
#   # SHOPIFY_CUSTOMER_SCOPE=...                        # optional; default matches below
#
# Shopify admin prerequisites (one-time), under
# Sales channels -> Headless -> <storefront> -> Customer Account API:
#   1. Settings -> Customer accounts -> enable "New customer accounts".
#   2. Client type -> set to CONFIDENTIAL (the store advertises
#      client_secret_basic). That reveals the Client Secret. A Public client also
#      works — the BFF then falls back to PKCE-only — but confidential is safer.
#   3. Application setup -> Callback URI(s) = the BFF callback, NOT a React route:
#        https://<prod-domain>/api/auth/callback
#      Logout URI = your site origin. Leave "Javascript origin(s)" EMPTY — the
#      BFF talks to Shopify server-to-server, so no browser origin is involved.
#   4. Scopes must come from the store's own `scopes_supported` (see
#      https://<shop>.myshopify.com/.well-known/openid-configuration):
#        openid email customer-account-api:full
#      The URL-style ".../auth/customer.graphql" scope is NOT accepted.
#
# Endpoints are auto-discovered from the two .well-known documents; SHOPIFY_SHOP_ID
# only backs the offline fallback. New customer accounts serve auth from
# shopify.com/authentication/<shopId>, not from the shop domain.


# --- Newsletter + lifecycle emails (Admin API) ---
# The "Join the LOOK Community" band + timed popup POST to /api/newsletter/subscribe,
# which marks the email SUBSCRIBED and sends the welcome email. Creating a customer
# needs the ADMIN API — the public Storefront token can't. These are SECRETS; they
# must NOT be VITE_-prefixed (never ship them to the browser).
#
# Shopify's own "Welcome new subscribers" automation is deliberately NOT used (and
# should be left OFF in Messaging -> Automations): it only fires on an unsubscribed
# -> subscribed transition, which a customer created already-subscribed never emits.
# We send all three lifecycle emails ourselves — see the EMAIL section below.
#
# Shopify (Spring '26) creates custom apps in the DEV DASHBOARD, which hands you a
# Client ID + Secret rather than a ready-made token. The function exchanges them for a
# 24h token automatically (client_credentials grant) and refreshes it — nothing to
# rotate by hand. Setup: Settings -> Apps and sales channels -> Develop apps ->
# "Build apps in Dev Dashboard" -> Create app -> add the Admin API scopes below and
# Release -> install on the store -> copy Client ID + Secret.
#
#   read_customers, write_customers   create/subscribe customers, once-only metafields
#   read_products, write_products     find newly published products, tag them announced
#   read_metaobjects                  read the client-editable `email_template` copy
#
#   SHOPIFY_ADMIN_CLIENT_ID=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#   SHOPIFY_ADMIN_CLIENT_SECRET=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#   # SHOPIFY_ADMIN_API_VERSION=2025-07   # optional; defaults in code
#
# Alternatively, if you already have a static Admin API token, set it instead and the
# function uses it directly (skips the exchange):
#   # SHOPIFY_ADMIN_TOKEN=shpat_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#
# Unset entirely (as in dev), /api/newsletter/subscribe returns 500 and the SPA falls
# back to a dev-success state, so the UI still works under plain `vite`.


# --- Lifecycle email (Resend) ---
# Three emails are sent from the BFF, never from the browser:
#   1. newsletter welcome  — /api/newsletter/subscribe, on a genuine new subscribe
#   2. account welcome     — /api/account/welcome, on a customer's first sign-in
#   3. new-drop digest     — /api/cron/new-drop, daily, for newly published products
# Copy for all three is editable by the client in a Shopify `email_template`
# metaobject (see api/_lib/email/content.ts); only the layout lives in code.
#
#   RESEND_API_KEY=re_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx    # SECRET, server-only
#   EMAIL_FROM=LOOK <hello@look.ind.in>           # any address on the verified domain
#   EMAIL_REPLY_TO=looksupport.in@gmail.com       # where replies actually land
#   CRON_SECRET=<32+ random hex chars>            # Vercel sends this as a Bearer token
#
# The From address needs NO mailbox — Resend signs it with the domain's DKIM key and
# Reply-To steers replies to the real support inbox. Add the domain in Resend and
# create the MX + TXT records it prints (plus a DMARC TXT, p=none to start).
#
# Unset RESEND_API_KEY (as in dev) and the sender logs each message to the console
# instead of sending, so the whole pipeline is testable without a key or a domain.
